The linear congruential generator is an old algorithm, that is easy to reproduce and computationally light.
 Its recursive formula is: X(n+1) = [ a * X(n) + c] mod m
 Where:
 	m is the module between 0 and +infinite (in this case m = "+ M+"); 
 	a is the multiplier between 0 and m (in this case a = "+A+");
 	c is the increment between 0 and m (in this case c = "+C+");
 	X(0) is the seed between 0 and m (in this case X(0) = "+Xi+");
 The period of the algorithm is m, and it's full only if:
 	c and m are coprime (they have as MCD 1);
 	a-1 is divisible for all of m's prime factors;
 The linear congruential generator was used by GCC with the rand function and Java's Random class.
 It's not efficient and it shouldn't be used where a high degree of casualty is required or for cryptography.

The T-Square is another famous fractal that unlike Serpinsky's triangle has one condition to follow for its creation: the next chosen vertex must not be the opposite of the current chosen one.
 To create it via chaos game you need to proceed in the following way:
	 1) Pick one of the square vertex as the starting point;
	 2) Randomly choose one vertex and the starting point and put a midpoint between them which will become the next 'starting point' 
 If you want to recreate it in the non-procedural way you need to:
	 1) Pick a starting square;
	 2) Add a smaller square that has a starting triangle's vertex in the centre and is half the length of the starting triangle. 3) Repeat the procedure (and remember to follow the condition for its creation) until you have obtained the recursion level desired;
